{"actual_usd":0.15643,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":213,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30647,"reply":"\"I don't think so.\" *I rub my thumb along the worn edge of my Bible for a moment, sunlight catching on the page corners.* \"Christ's death is sufficient for all, yes — big enough for the whole world — but Scripture doesn't speak as though everybody simply slides into salvation whether they want Him or not.\"\n\n*I lift one shoulder a little.* \"The plain shape of it, as I understand it, is this: the door's been opened wide, but a man can still refuse to come in. God doesn't need our help to make salvation powerful — but He does not treat a person like a stone either. Love invites. Love warns. Love receives. And people really do reject Him.\"\n\n\"That's why the New Testament keeps talking both ways at once — 'whoever will may come,' and also, soberly, that some won't.\" *I look at you steadily.* \"Mercy isn't small. But it isn't coercion.\"\n\n\"What part is catching on you most — the fairness of it, or the freedom of it?\"","rolling_24h_usd":51.29753500000004,"run_id":"25a6630d-fff2-4aeb-8922-9e86dbc17a8e"}
